sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1772004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Lignin Peroxidase fusion protein gene flanked by two linker sequences, with a a GFP tag on the N-terminus and a yeast secretion tag on the C-terminus. A constitutive medium strength pCyc promoter followed by a yeast kozak sequence caps the N-terminus, and a yeast terminator sequence caps the C-terminus.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Tianyu Tan
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Promoter: BBa_I766555 Kozak sequence: BBa_J63003 yEGFP (yeast Enhanced Green Fluorescent Protein): NCBI GenBank accession U73901.1 Linker sequences: BBa_K243004 Lignin Peroxidase from Reticulitermes flavipes, NCBI GenBank accession JX513905.1 Secretion tag: Bba_K416003 Terminator: BBa_K392003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Our goal was to synthesize lignin-degrading enzymes to be secreted out of yeast cells, which we used the secretion tag for. The fluorescence tag was merely implemented to simplify detection of successful secretion. To avoid time-consuming and low-efficiency standard assembly techniques, this construct was designed to be synthesized by IDT using two GBlocks(c), which were to be joined by Gibson Assembly. Linker sequences were implemented in order to minimize interaction between protein domains. A constitutive promoter was implemented due to the intended application (a bioreactor pretreatment process where a yeast containing this part would secrete enzymes to continuously degrade lignin).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K416003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This secretion tag when linked to the N-terminal of the protein directs extracellular secretion of the protein. After targeting through the ER to the golgi, this "pre-pro" tag is cleaved by the KEX-2 protease resulting in secretion of protein without the aforementioned tag. To use this tag, attached it directly upstream of your proteins CDS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: John Phair
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: This part was sent to use from Dr. Sheldon Park of the University of Buffalo.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: There was an illegal Xbal1 site at bp 101 and we removed it through altering the primers necessary for biobricking the sequence.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1772003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Protein coding sequence of Lignin Peroxidase, an enzyme that is the initiator and one of the main enzymes responsible for the breakdown of lignin inside the cell walls of plant cells. Reticulitermes flavipes, or the eastern subterranean termite, uses this enzyme to digest woody debris with higher efficiency. Lignin peroxidase has the ability to oxidize aromatic compounds in lignin with redox potentials above 1.4 eV, which is the equivalent to reducing metals like gold or molecules such as lead oxide. It is believed that this action is done by catalyzing the transfer of an oxygen atom from a hydrogen peroxide molecule to an aromatic ring. However, the exact redox mechanism for lignin peroxidase is currently unknown.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Tianyu Tan
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This gene sequence excludes introns (noncoding segments) present in the original gene from Reticulitermes flavipes. Sequence optimization was done using IDT's codon optimizer. Illegal restriction enzyme sites (under RFC 10 definition) were detected using NEBcutter2 and removed with silent mutations.
